results.name: Decimal expansion of the prime zeta function at 9.
comment: Mathar's Table 1 (cited below) lists expansions of the prime zeta function at integers s in 10..39. - _Jason Kimberley_, Jan 07 2017
reference: Henri Cohen, Number Theory, Volume II: Analytic and Modern Tools, GTM Vol. 240, Springer, 2007; see pp. 208-209.
J. W. L. Glaisher, On the Sums of Inverse Powers of the Prime Numbers, Quart. J. Math. 25, 347-362, 1891.
link: Jason Kimberley, Table of n, a(n) for n = -2..1999
Henri Cohen, High Precision Computation of Hardy-Littlewood Constants, Preprint, 1998.
Henri Cohen, High-precision computation of Hardy-Littlewood constants. [pdf copy, with permission]
X. Gourdon and P. Sebah, Some Constants from Number theory
R. J. Mathar, Series of reciprocal powers of k-almost primes, arXiv:0803.0900 [math.NT], 2008-2009. Table 1.
Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, Prime Zeta Function
mathematica: pz9[n_] := pz9[n] = Join[{0, 0}, Sum[ MoebiusMu[k]*Log[Zeta[9*k]]/k, {k, 1, n}] // RealDigits[#, 10, 103]& // First]; pz9[100]; pz9[n = 200]; While[pz9[n] != pz9[n - 100], n = n + 100]; pz9[n] (* _Jean-François Alcover_, Feb 14 2013, from formula *)
RealDigits[ PrimeZetaP[ 9], 10, 111][[1]] (* _Robert G. Wilson v_, Sep 03 2014 *)
xref: Decimal expansion of the prime zeta function: A085548 (at 2), A085541 (at 3), A085964 (at 4) to A085968 (at 8), this sequence (at 9).
